# DESIGN.md First UI Rule

When implementing or refactoring UI in `assemblymes`, default to a `DESIGN.md`-driven workflow.

## Source of truth

- Prefer a root-level `DESIGN.md` as the visual contract for UI generation.
- If `DESIGN.md` is missing and the task is UI-heavy, ask to add one or draft one before major UI changes.
- Use the structure popularized by `awesome-design-md` (theme, palette, typography, components, layout, responsive behavior).

## Required behavior for UI tasks

- Before coding substantial UI changes, summarize which visual tokens/rules are being applied.
- Keep visual consistency across pages (colors, spacing scale, radius, typography hierarchy, component states).
- Avoid ad-hoc one-off styles that conflict with `DESIGN.md` unless explicitly requested.
- For any new page, include at minimum: heading hierarchy, spacing rhythm, button/input states, and empty/loading/error visuals.

## Communication expectation

- In delivery notes, briefly map UI outcomes back to the selected `DESIGN.md` principles.
- If no `DESIGN.md` is present, state that explicitly and list the temporary style assumptions.
